                        </handDesc>
                        <decoDesc>
                            <summary>An initial folio features the illuminated opening on presumably
                                    <locus from="1b" to="1b">folio 1b</locus>, while twenty-six
                                illustrations feature the following scenes:</summary>
                            <decoNote type="headpiece"><label>Opening:</label> A detached
                                illuminated opening of the work features a domed scalloped mandorla
                                surmounted by a detached gold medallion, with split cloud-collar
                                motifs between at right at left, with a blank horizontal gilt
                                cartouche with within a rectangle below, infilled floral scrollwork
                                set against an ultramarine ground.</decoNote>
                            <decoNote><label>Illustrations:</label>
                                <list rend="numbered">
                                    <item n="1"><title>Chapter 2 on Sincerity</title><lb/>
                                        <desc>King enthroned outdoors attended by two young men at
                                            left, executed on a bright coral ground. The margin at
                                            left features a youth holding a bound captive while an
                                            older man and youth discuss the scene from above. It
                                            illustrates a scene where a ruler forgives a captive who
                                            insulted him.</desc><lb/>
                                        <dimensions type="illustration" unit="mm">
                                            <height>120</height>
                                            <width>92</width>
                                        </dimensions>
                                    </item>
                                    <lb/>
                                    <item n="2"><title>Chapter 3 on Prayer</title><lb/>
                                        <desc>Battle scene, with slain soliders at right. It
                                            illustrates a passage on employing prayer to avert the
                                            evil a violent conflict.</desc><lb/>
                                        <dimensions type="illustration" unit="mm">
                                            <height>164</height>
                                            <width>119</width>
                                        </dimensions>
                                    </item>
                                    <lb/>
                                    <item n="3"><title>Chapter 3 on Prayer, con't</title><lb/>
                                        <desc>A young prince, a youth, a bearded man, who removes
                                            his turban, and a dervish seated on his sheepskin in the
                                            right margin all pray in gratitude under a golden sky,
                                            after a torrential, days-long devastating rainstorm
                                            concludes. overhead, while watches.</desc><lb/>
                                        <dimensions type="illustration" unit="mm">
                                            <height>116</height>
                                            <width>133</width>
                                        </dimensions><lb/>
                                        <note>Catchword present at lower-left.</note>
                                    </item>
                                    <lb/>

                                    <item n="4"><title>Chapter 8 on Modesty</title><lb/>
                                        <desc>A youth and bearded man in foreground approach a king
                                            and his attendant on horseback, while another bearded
                                            man watches from the right margin. It illustrates a
                                            scene where a man offers a ruler turbid water he
                                            believes tastes sweet as he never tasted truly sweet
                                            water before, but the king responds with kindness and
                                            rewards him.</desc><lb/>
                                        <dimensions type="illustration" unit="mm">
                                            <height>104</height>
                                            <width>100</width>
                                        </dimensions><lb/>
                                        <note>Catchword present at lower-left.</note>
                                    </item>
                                    <lb/>
                                    <item n="5"><title>Chapter 12 on Resolve</title><lb/>
                                        <desc>A bearded man kneels before an enthroned prince
                                            outdoors in a rocky landscape, with attendants at left
                                            and right, while youth stands in the foreground, and two
                                            horses graze in the right margin. It illustrates a story
                                            of a prince who habitually ate clay resulting in
                                            infirmity. A darvish encourages him to strive for
                                            resolve to overcome his dilemma.</desc><lb/>
                                        <dimensions type="illustration" unit="mm">
                                            <height>91</height>
                                            <width>114</width>
                                        </dimensions><lb/>
                                        <note>Catchword present at lower-left.</note>
                                    </item>
                                    <lb/>
                                    <item n="6"><title>Chapter 15 on Forgiveness</title><lb/>
                                        <desc>An old woman and cow approach Sassanian king Qubād
                                            enthroned, with two attendants beside him, while a youth
                                            in the right margin watches. It illustrates a scene
                                            where the woman disrespectfully permits her cow to soil
                                            carpets indoors, which the king forgives.  </desc><lb/>
                                        <dimensions type="illustration" unit="mm">
                                            <height>91</height>
                                            <width>114</width>
                                        </dimensions><lb/>
                                        <note>Catchword present at lower-left.</note>
                                    </item>
                                    <lb/>
                                    <item n="7"><title>Chapter 15 on Justice</title><lb/>
                                        <desc>A king sits enthroned, eyes closed, while another king
                                            approaches with two attendants, one outside the margin
                                            and a groom tends to two horses behind rocks at right.
                                            It illustrates a scene where an attendant to the king
                                            suffers a scorpion bite but still maintains his
                                            composure before the king. </desc><lb/>
                                        <dimensions type="illustration" unit="mm">
                                            <height>153</height>
                                            <width>118</width>
                                        </dimensions><lb/>
                                        <note>Catchword present at lower-left.</note>
                                    </item>
                                    <lb/>

                                    <item n="8"><title>Chapter 17 on Gentleness</title><lb/>
                                        <desc><persName key="person_89661385" role="dpc">Imām
                                                Ḥusayn</persName> stands with a flaming aureole that
                                            extends into the upper margin, attended a servant and
                                            two youths.</desc><lb/>
                                        <dimensions type="illustration" unit="mm">
                                            <height>72</height>
                                            <width>98</width>
                                        </dimensions><lb/>
                                        <dimensions type="aureolin" unit="mm">
                                            <height>31</height>
                                            <width>17</width>
                                        </dimensions>
                                    </item>
                                    <lb/>
                                    <item n="9"><title>Chapter 21 on Benevolence and Charity</title><lb/>
                                        <desc>An elderly man at right docks his boat at a pier by
                                            the ocean, attended by a youth while other young men
                                            approach from the right.</desc><lb/>
